      <item>
         <title><![CDATA[Pitfalls of coding emails — lessons learned (part 1)]]></title>
         <link>https://medium.com/ida-mediafoundry/pitfalls-of-coding-emails-lessons-learned-part-1-7532803ead2c?source=rss----a1a776694b7a---4</link>
         <guid isPermaLink="false">https://medium.com/p/7532803ead2c</guid>
         <category><![CDATA[web-development]]></category>
         <category><![CDATA[email]]></category>
         <category><![CDATA[adobe]]></category>
         <category><![CDATA[marketing-automation]]></category>
         <category><![CDATA[campaign]]></category>
         <dc:creator><![CDATA[Andro Delrue]]></dc:creator>
         <pubDate>Tue, 03 Jul 2018 08:01:01 GMT</pubDate>
         <atom:updated>2018-10-21T09:49:57.751Z</atom:updated>
         <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><em>Expects the reader to have a basic knowledge of coding (responsive) emails</em></p><figure><img alt="" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/1*o6hiCteU7wHTzKhTauIPzg.jpeg" /></figure><p>I already had some experience involving the creation of (responsive) emails, but as it turns out with my latest project, there is still much to learn. You always keep your fingers crossed when you put your HTML to the test on whatever email testing platform you use, hoping the result isn’t too bad.</p><p>You’d expect, being 2018, that email design would evolve over time like web design did, but no, it didn’t… If you ask me, it became even worse, looking back on the last decade.</p><p>There are some solutions in the shape of frameworks that do much of the heavy lifting for you, for example <a href="https://mjml.io/">MJML</a> and <a href="https://foundation.zurb.com/emails.html">Foundation for Emails</a> to name a few. And that’s great, but I’m not sold on them yet.</p><blockquote>Frameworks bring issues…</blockquote><p>Something doesn’t work or something else is not possible, maybe there is some code bloating etc. Call me old-fashioned, but I still prefer making my emails in plain old tables without the need of learning/using framework syntax that transpiles into HTML.</p><p>In this two-part special, I will cover the most common — and lesser common — pitfalls regarding coding emails. So, without further ado…</p><h4>Using web fonts in emails</h4><p>For this first issue, I stumbled upon an <a href="https://litmus.com/blog/the-ultimate-guide-to-web-fonts">article</a> with a possible solution. I used the method that they find most bulletproof: the @font-face method. They describe how you can get the CSS by copy/pasting the web font URL in the browser, et voilà… It returns the font format that is best for that particular browser.</p><p>But what if you want all web font formats, like I do i.e. eot, ttf, svg, woff and woff2? What do you do then? Looking up which browser serves what format, download that browser and copy/paste the web font URL in each and every one of them?</p><p>No. A colleague of mine gave me a tip: <a href="https://www.fontsquirrel.com/tools/webfont-generator">fontsquirrel’s web font generator</a>. In case of a Google Font, download the font you selected and upload the font styles you want to generate. Select the ‘Expert’ option, because ttf, eot and svg are not generated by default. The only thing I changed is the Truetype Hinting which I set to ‘Keep Existing’, because I assume Google optimized it already.</p><p>Once downloaded, you will find a CSS file which contains all font-faces:</p><pre><a href="http://twitter.com/font">@font</a>-face {<br> font-family: &#39;latobold&#39;;<br> ...<br> font-weight: normal;<br> font-style: normal;<br>}</pre><pre>@font-face {<br> font-family: &#39;latobold_italic&#39;;<br> ...<br> font-weight: normal;<br> font-style: normal;<br>}</pre><p>What I suggest you do is make the font-family name generic and set the styling accordingly.</p><pre>@font-face {<br> font-family: &#39;Lato&#39;;<br> ...<br> font-weight: bold;<br> font-style: normal;<br>}</pre><pre>@font-face {<br> font-family: &#39;Lato&#39;;<br> ...<br> font-weight: bold;<br> font-style: italic;<br>}</pre><p>That way, you only have one name per font-family, which is much easier. The last thing you need to do is serve the font files on your server and change the source URL’s and that’s it!</p><h4>What about email clients that do not support web fonts?</h4><p>Easy, you just provide a fallback font in your styling:</p><pre>font-family: ‘Lato’, Helvetica, sans-serif;</pre><p>This turned out to be too easy though.</p><p>If you would test this in Outlook, you would notice that nor the Lato, nor the Helvetica font is rendered, but Times New Roman. No matter what font you choose as fallback, it keeps going back to the Times one. There are some hacks (as described in the article I mentioned in the beginning), so I went for the second one: the media query.</p><p>Turns out not only Outlook ignores everything inside a media query, by the way, Internet Explorer does as well. So, if you want to view your email in the browser and that browser happens to be IE, you will see your fallback font rendered.</p><p>No problem, the conditional comment hack works for Outlook too, without breaking anything else in the process. Just use the class everywhere you use your font-family property and you’re done, right?</p><p>Well… there is a catch. Take the following example:</p><pre>&lt;table class=&quot;header fontFallback&quot;&gt;</pre><p>Outlook will not find the fontFallback class therefore will not render the fallback because it only renders one class and it’s the first one. The solution is to put it at the beginning, take a deep breath and leave your frustrations behind you.</p><p>Your work is done (for real now).</p><h4>A thing about buttons and emails</h4><p>The days of using an image as a button, belongs to the past (I used to do that, you know). It was just easier this way because making it look good for all mail clients was a real pain in the… well, you know what I&#39;m getting at.</p><p>Nowadays, there are more than enough solutions to help you out, and I found mine <a href="https://litmus.com/blog/a-guide-to-bulletproof-buttons-in-email-design">here</a>: the padding + border-based approach. It just works!</p><p>Couple of side notes:</p><ul><li>You have to include a border or the padding won’t render in Outlook</li><li>I explicitly set the line-height as well because the button would be higher on Pixel Outlook if you choose not to include it</li></ul><h4>Making emails responsive</h4><p>If putting emails together with tables and inline styling isn’t hard and time-consuming enough, try to make them responsive. With more and more people using their mobile devices to read mails, there is no more escaping the responsive-game.</p><blockquote>If you want to be taken seriously and look professional towards your subscribers when sending out your email campaign, you have to go responsive!</blockquote><p>I used to have two responsive style blocks: one at the bottom, before the closing body tag, and one in the head tag.</p><p>Why are there two you ask? In March 2015, Yahoo supported the use of media queries on mobile, but it didn’t allow style tags in the head. The fix was to put it in the body, easy. But then you have Gmail on mobile, which only supports style tags in head and not in the body.</p><p><em>Before Yahoo media query support, you had to use attribute selectors in your responsive styling due to a </em><a href="https://www.emailonacid.com/blog/article/email-development/stop_yahoo_mail_from_rendering_your_media_queries/"><em>bug</em></a><em> in Yahoo. Attribute selectors in Gmail, on the other hand, are not supported.</em></p><p>Anyway, there is a hack to make Yahoo stop stripping your style and that is by adding another (empty) head tag above your main head tag, This way Yahoo strips the first head tag and leaves the other one containing your styling alone. This is great, because this means you can remove the responsive styling inside your body tag. Awesome!</p><h4><strong>Showing/hiding content in responsive emails</strong></h4><p>Let&#39;s say you have two elements, one for desktop and one for mobile. By default you want to hide the mobile version, so you add display: none to the inline styling of your wrapper element. The web version of Yahoo mail doesn’t seem to care about the statement because it will just show the mobile version.</p><pre>&lt;table cellpadding=&quot;0&quot; cellspacing=&quot;0&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; class=&quot;mobile&quot; style=&quot;display: none;&quot;&gt;<br> &lt;tr&gt;<br>  &lt;td&gt;Mobile content&lt;/td&gt;<br> &lt;/tr&gt;<br>&lt;/table&gt;</pre><p>This can easily be fixed by adding the following in your style tag above your media query:</p><pre>.mobile {<br> display: none;<br>}</pre><p><strong>Quick tip</strong>: you might think that the inline declaration is now redundant, but I would suggest you leave it there. For some reason your responsive version doesn’t work (anymore) on Outlook for mobile. Without the declaration it would display the mobile content as well.</p><p>Who knew hiding something would be such a hassle?</p><p>Luckily showing something on mobile is more straightforward:</p><pre>@media screen and (max-width: 600px) {<br> .mobile {<br>  display: none !important;<br> }<br>}</pre><p>This will work (sighs), but not on Yahoo mobile…</p><p>There are a couple of properties that do not work if the “!important“ statement and the property value have a space between them, and display is one of them. So this will resolve the issue:</p><pre>display: none!important</pre><p>Do this for all your properties so you won’t get any more surprises (hopefully).</p><h3><strong>Stay tuned…</strong></h3><p>This concludes part 1 on how to handle the issues that come with coding your own emails. Stay tuned for part 2, where I will give you some more useful tips and tricks!</p><figure><a href="https://www.ida-mediafoundry.be/"><img alt="" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/960/1*1nmvJQfkqYDTkSGtbWpKkw.png" /></a></figure><figure><a href="https://www.ida-mediafoundry.be/nl/jobs.html"><img alt="" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/480/1*CmJeDyI92a6wdUXsxr3JqQ.png" /></a></figure><figure><a href="https://medium.com/ida-mediafoundry"><img alt="" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/480/1*HxprJR4afmWbGfoA1-Wh1A.png" /></a></figure><img src="https://medium.com/_/stat?event=post.clientViewed&referrerSource=full_rss&postId=7532803ead2c" width="1" height="1"><hr><p><a href="https://medium.com/ida-mediafoundry/pitfalls-of-coding-emails-lessons-learned-part-1-7532803ead2c">Pitfalls of coding emails — lessons learned (part 1)</a> was originally published in <a href="https://medium.com/ida-mediafoundry">ida mediafoundry</a> on Medium, where people are continuing the conversation by highlighting and responding to this story.</p>]]></content:encoded>
